Objectives

  • Understand types of missing data
  • Visualize missing data

Missing Data Frameworks

The topic of missing data is an important one. Our natural tendencies are to dismiss missing data and focus on the data points that we have, in order to focus on models, predictions, hypotheses testing and classification. But analysis of missing data can alert us to fundamental issues in our data collection, reporting, or input that can affect the quality of our analyses and predictions.

Missing data falls into 3 categories:

  • MCAR - Missing Completely At Random
  • MAR - Missing At Random
  • MNAR - Missing Not At Random

Well discuss these scenarios along with methods to evaluate and impute missing data.

MCAR - Missing Completely at Random

MCAR data happens when the events that cause missing data are completely independent of the observed data and the unobserved variables, and happens entirely by chance. MCAR is the easiest case to deal with, because we can assume that the missingness has no bias on estimates and no impact on an analysis. Unfortunately, this type of missingness is rarely the case.

  • independent of observed
  • no impact on estimates or analysis
  • rare

MAR - Missing At Random

MAR data distinguishes itself from MCAR data when there is a mechanism that accounts for the missingness. In particular, there might be systematic differences between the missing and observed values, but these can be entirely explained by other observed variables. (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4121561/) In other words, the missingness isnt related to its own value but is related to the values of other variable in the dataset.

An example of MAR is failure to report income level based on gender. One gender (a variable included in the dataset) might not fill out income level more than another gender.

  • systematic difference between missing and observed
  • is related to values of other variables
  • impacts estimates and analysis
  • more common

MNAR - Missing Not At Random

Lastly, we have the scenario where the data are not missing at random, but the missingness is related to the variable itself. This type of missingness is considered non-ignorable and may suggest systematic failures in data collection or recording methods.

Example of MNAR could be that non-compliant diabetic subjects fail to report blood sugar levels more than pre-diabetics, or obese subjects fail to report weight more than other subjects.

  • related to the variable itself
  • suggests data collection or recording issues
  • impacts estimates and analysis
  • more common

Missing value strategies

Missing value strategies based on non-ignorable or problematic missing values could include:

  • Reviewing data collection methods
  • Reconsidering study design
  • Reviewing data coding or input methods
  • Dropping cases with missing values
  • Imputing missing values

Missing data in R

Recall that missing data in R is represented by NA. A blank is not the same thing as missing!

R also has support for nan (not a number), and inf (infinity). These are not all equal!

# Sample missing data
x1 <- 
  c(1,2,NA,NaN,Inf,3,999)

# this detects only the nan
x1[is.nan(x1)]
## [1] NaN
# this misses infinity, but gets the NA and the NaN
x1[is.na(x1)]
## [1]  NA NaN
# this detect infinity but misses the NA and NaN
x1[is.infinite(x1)]
## [1] Inf
  • We should use the NA operator for missing data. We can recode the data manually by replacing any odd values as missing:
# recode 99 and 999 to NA
x1[x1 %in% c(999,99)] <- NA
# recode Inf and NaN to NA
x1[is.nan(x1) | is.infinite(x1)] <- NA
x1
## [1]  1  2 NA NA NA  3 NA
  • And here are some character examples:
x2 <- 
  c('a','b',NA,'',' ')
# catches NA but not the blanks
is.na(x2)
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
x2[is.na(x2)]
## [1] NA
# returns the blank and NA for the NA!
x2 == ''
## [1] FALSE FALSE    NA  TRUE FALSE
x2[x2 == '']
## [1] NA ""
# returns the space and NA for the NA!
x2[x2 == ' ']
## [1] NA  " "
# recode
x2[x2 %in% c('',' ')] <- NA
x2
## [1] "a" "b" NA  NA  NA

Recoding Missing Values

We can recode missing values in a variety of ways:

  • by combining detection and setting patterns
  • by using convenience functions

Recoding Missing Values in base and dplyr

In base R, we can use ifelse to recode values in a vector. In dplyr, if we want to recode sentinel values as missing values, we can do so within a mutate statement and use na_if

library(dplyr)
a <- c(1,2,-999)
ifelse(a==-999,NA,a) # if it matches, replace with NA, otherwise pass the value through
## [1]  1  2 NA
#
df <- tibble::tibble(A=c(1,2,-999),B=c('Unknown','red','blue'))
df
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##       A B      
##   <dbl> <chr>  
## 1     1 Unknown
## 2     2 red    
## 3  -999 blue
df %>% 
  mutate(A = ifelse(A==-999,NA,A)) #as above
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##       A B      
##   <dbl> <chr>  
## 1     1 Unknown
## 2     2 red    
## 3    NA blue
df %>% 
  mutate(A = na_if(A,-999)) # or using the convenience function
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##       A B      
##   <dbl> <chr>  
## 1     1 Unknown
## 2     2 red    
## 3    NA blue

Recoding Multiple Columns in dplyr

For multiple columns, we need to do a little bit more programming, and use helper verbs. However, na_if can only handle one sentinel value. If you have to recode multiple values, you need to chain statements together.

df %>% 
  mutate_all(~na_if(.x,-999))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##       A B      
##   <dbl> <chr>  
## 1     1 Unknown
## 2     2 red    
## 3    NA blue
df %>% 
  mutate_all(~na_if(.x,-999)) %>% 
  mutate_all(~na_if(.x,"Unknown"))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##       A B    
##   <dbl> <chr>
## 1     1 <NA> 
## 2     2 red  
## 3    NA blue

Recoding In data.table

  • We can recode in data.table using our assignment operator and a matching condition in I
  • We can chain statements together
library(data.table)
dt <- data.table(df)
dt
##       A       B
## 1:    1 Unknown
## 2:    2     red
## 3: -999    blue
dt[A==-999,A:=NA]
#
dt[A==-999,A:=NA][B=="Unknown",B:=NA]
dt
##     A    B
## 1:  1 <NA>
## 2:  2  red
## 3: NA blue

Horse Colic

Horse colic is a common (4-10%) and potentially life-threatening condition for horses. Its a condition that represents intestinal pain, can onset suddenly, and can require expensive surgery. It is the leading cause of death for domesticated horses. This data represents several veterinary features related to horse colic.

How much missing?

Lets analyze how much of this data set is missing. We can think about this two ways - quantifying missingness by row, or quantifying missingness by column.

We will start by column. There are a few ways to do this, but I chose to use the apply function and identify the function should be applied across the columns. The result is the total number of missing per column.

## total missing by column
missing_column <- 
  apply(colic,MARGIN = 2,function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
missing_column
##                     surgery                   young_age                 hospital_ID                 rectal_temp                       pulse 
##                           1                           0                           0                          60                          24 
##                   resp_rate            extremities_temp            peripheral_pulse            mucous_membranes             cap_refill_time 
##                          58                          56                          69                          47                          32 
##                        pain                 peristalsis        abdominal_distension            nasogastric_tube          nasogastric_reflux 
##                          55                          44                          56                         104                         106 
##                   ng_rfx_PH                       feces                     abdomen          packed_cell_volume               total_protein 
##                         247                         102                         118                          29                          33 
## abdominocentesis_appearance            abcs_tot_protein                     outcome 
##                         165                         198                           1
# change the margins
par(mar = c(5,14,4,2))
barplot(missing_column,
        horiz = TRUE,
        las = 2)

Missing by Row

We can also analyze this by row by changing the margin argument. This results in a vector as long as the original number of rows, so I have further summarized it a bit (rather than print hundreds of values!)

## total missing by row
missing_row <- 
  apply(colic,MARGIN = 1,function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
head(missing_row)
## [1]  6  5  5  1 12  8
## How many rows are missing 5 or more?
sum(missing_row>5) # 108
## [1] 108
sum(missing_row>5)/length(missing_row) # 36%
## [1] 0.36

Visualizing the missing Data

There is a handy and simple package called visdat that will visualize the missing data for us as well. But this wont work very well for big datasets.

# use the visdat package to visualize the missing
library(visdat)
library(ggplot2)
plt1 <- vis_miss(colic)
# I manually changed the margins here so the text doesn't clip. 
# This function returns a ggplot so I must use that too...
plt1 +
  theme(plot.margin = unit(c(0.5,3,0.5,0.5), "cm"))

# this would be more challenging to use with a lot of rows though!

Drop rows with missing data

Assessing missing at random versus missing completely at random

Recall it is hard (or impossible) to test for missing not at random, since I dont know what I dont know.

However, we can try to assess missingness and see if it seems to be related to other variables in the dataset. One way to do that is to use the naniar package, which has a nice extra piece added on to ggplot to examine distributions. We will focus on pulse and rectal temp in this dataset for now.

Here is an example of one way to examine the distribution across missing / non-missing status. Notice the regular ggplot call excludes missing values:

ggplot(colic,
       aes(x = rectal_temp,
           y = pulse)) + 
  geom_point()

However, if we add naniar and the geom_miss_point(), we will get a distribution of points along the X and Y axis that allow us to examine the distribution of missing versus non-missing values.

library(naniar)
# Missing values are added along the X and Y axis
ggplot(colic,
       aes(x = rectal_temp,
           y = pulse)) + 
  geom_miss_point()

The red data points in the lower left corner are where both variables are missing. That is not useful to see here. However, the red points along the bottom of the graph are missing pulse but not missing rectal temperature. The question we ask ourselves then is, Does this distribution look different than the distribution right above it?

We could try to ask that question more directly by simply calculating some summary statistics across the missing and non missing values as well.

# check average pulse across missing rectal temp
colic[,list(mean_pulse = mean(pulse,na.rm=T)),
      by = list(rt_miss = is.na(rectal_temp))]
##    rt_miss mean_pulse
## 1:   FALSE   70.23504
## 2:    TRUE   81.26190

It looks like the mean pulse of horses missing rectal temp is higher than the mean pulse in those not missing rectal temp. This would support the idea that the missingness in rectal temp is MAR instead of MCAR, since it seems to be related to pulse. That is a bit harder to see in the graph above though. Sometimes it is better to directly code / calculate these things

Imputing the mean or median in a dataset

So what to do if we have missing data? We could consider simply imputing one value based on the full distribution of only that value. One method of doing that would be imputing the mean (or the median). In the case of the pulse variable, we would simply write code like the following:

# copy dataset first
colic_new <- 
  copy(colic)
# convert int to numeric
colic_new[,pulse := as.numeric(pulse)]
# impute mean by column
colic_new[,
          pulse_mean_impute:=pulse]
colic_new[is.na(pulse),
          pulse_mean_impute:=colic_new[,mean(pulse,na.rm=TRUE)]]
# what happened?
hist(colic_new$pulse,15)

hist(colic_new$pulse_mean_impute,15)

Notice that there is now a big bump at the mean value. So we have not biased the mean, but we have biased the spread of the data (the standard deviation).

I am going to add two more columns of imputation. One will impute all missing values as low values (the 5th percentile), and the other will impute all values as high values (the 95th percentile). This will allow a sensitivity test in a moment.

# impute p5 by column
colic_new[,
          pulse_low_impute:=pulse]
colic_new[is.na(pulse),
          pulse_low_impute:=colic_new[,quantile(pulse,0.05,na.rm=TRUE)]]
# what happened?
hist(colic_new$pulse,15)

hist(colic_new$pulse_low_impute,15)

# impute p95 by column
colic_new[,
          pulse_high_impute:=pulse]
colic_new[is.na(pulse),
          pulse_high_impute:=colic_new[,quantile(pulse,0.95,na.rm=TRUE)]]
# what happened?
hist(colic_new$pulse,15)

hist(colic_new$pulse_high_impute,15)

Sensitivity tests on missing data

Now we have three different versions of imputed data for the horse pulse.

Lets ask and answer the question, is mean horse pulse related to the outcome of interest? And is the answer to this question sensitive to the missing data?

The outcome of interest here is what happened to the horse. The outcome has three levels:

1 = lived 2 = died 3 = was euthanized

I will recode this to simply be lived or died by combining the died and euthanized categories.

colic_new[outcome == 1,outcome2 := 'lived']
colic_new[outcome %in% c(2,3),outcome2 := 'died']
colic_new[,table(outcome,outcome2)] # looks good
##        outcome2
## outcome died lived
##       1    0   178
##       2   77     0
##       3   44     0

Now we can do a basic analysis of the relationship between these two variables, using the various versions of pulse.

colic_new[!is.na(outcome2),
          mean(pulse,na.rm=T),by=outcome2]
##    outcome2       V1
## 1:     died 85.06422
## 2:    lived 63.42169
colic_new[!is.na(outcome2),
          mean(pulse_mean_impute,na.rm=T),by=outcome2]
##    outcome2       V1
## 1:     died 83.75997
## 2:    lived 63.99414
colic_new[!is.na(outcome2),
          mean(pulse_low_impute,na.rm=T),by=outcome2]
##    outcome2       V1
## 1:     died 80.59504
## 2:    lived 61.84270
colic_new[!is.na(outcome2),
          mean(pulse_high_impute,na.rm=T),by=outcome2]
##    outcome2       V1
## 1:     died 89.02479
## 2:    lived 67.57303

Look at these different results. Whether we ignore the missing data, impute the mean, impute it low, or impute it high, we still get the same qualitative answer to the analysis - horse who died had a much higher average pulse than horses who lived.

In this case, we would say the analysis is not sensitive to the missing data, so I feel safe ignoring it or imputing the mean.

If we had found something different - that the results depended on whether or not the missing values were high or low, then I would feel less confident in these results.
